<dl id="n03151c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03151c">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03151c"> 151(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Talked of Him <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03151c"> <li><a href="../../flex/z/lexfh.htm#n03151c">FH X</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03151c">MS BL 47473-16</ms> </li><li>JJA 46:284 <a name="e23d" href="../../FF/fdra/eda.htm#e23d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/e/e23d.htm#n03151c">Draft: I.5&sect;2.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">But Oscar Wilde was conscious of great ability and was driven by an inordinate vanity. Instead of diminishing his pretensions in the face of opposition he increased them. He began to go abroad in the evening in knee breeches and silk stockings wearing strange flowers in his coat&mdash;green cornflowers and gilded lilies&mdash;while talking about Baudelaire, whose name even was unfamiliar, as a world poet, and proclaiming the strange creed that &ldquo;nothing succeeds like excess.&rdquo; Very soon his name came into everyone&apos;s mouth; London <mark>talked of him</mark> and discussed him at a thousand tea-tables. <small> Frank Harris, <a name="FHOW2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FHOW2"><cite title="source">Oscar Wilde His Life and Confessions</cite></a> (1918) 64</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
